Birth weight data analysis

In this assignment we have been given the task of modelling birthweight as a function of the predictor variables. Please note you can click the hide button at the top of the page if inspecting this becomes tedious (it can be a helpful guide however).

Importing and examing the data

The first step in this analysis is to import, examine and (if neccesary) clean the data. To make life a lot easier, we are going to use the “tidyverse” suite of packages, which significantly upon the syntax, consistency and power of base R.

births.df <- read.csv("phbirths.csv")

From the summary, we can see that;

  • The majority of mothers in this dataset are Black (African American). This is not characteristic of the demographics of the United States or even Philadelphia generally (see census links below).

  • Years of education recieved ranges from 0 years (no schooling what so ever) to 17 years (Bachelors degree). On average, these mothers have a mean education of 12.3 years, about equivalent to a high school diploma. Naturally, we would expect some of these mothers (from a sample of ~1100) to be less than 18 years old and hence it would be impossible for them to have recieved more than 13 years of education.

  • Weeks of gestation ranges from 20 to 43. Gestations periods prior to 37 weeks are considered preterm births (premature). We can immediately see that less than 25% of babies are born premature (Q1 Gestation = 38 weeks). Gestation periods are further broken into moderate/late preterm (32-36 weeks), very preterm (28-31 weeks) and extremely preterm (28 weeks). From the minimum we can see at least one baby was born extremely preterm.

Issues with the data

On inspecting the data, we notice it has been encoded as “black” and “non-black”. My personal view is that African American is a more appropriate term (so I will continue to use this term), but this is a highly subjective and controversial issue. The United States census operates using either term.

United States Census Quick Facts

Philadelphia Demographics

There is also the issue that ethnicities should usually be recording with mutliple possible combinations; we live in increasingly diverse societies and restricting ethnicity selection to a single ethnicity is an archaic form of data recording, structuring and collection. To give an example, if an African American (AA) individual also identifies as Native Indian (NI), are they recorded as; AA-NI,NI-AA, AA or NI? Hence we make the assumption here that “black” observations relate to individuals identifying as only African American and “non-black” observations relate to individuals identifying as any possible combination of ethnicities including African American, but excluding the individuals only identifying as African American.

A similar resolution issue is also spotted with the “educ” variable reflecting years of education. No context is given as to how this measured (from pre, primary, middle or high school) and only integer values are recorded (despite the fact it is common to study for half a year at tertiary level, or complete half-year courses). Our assumptions in explaining this variable will be that is measures years of formal education (the US school system), starting from 1st year (usually age five) and only includes formal tertiary education (e.g. excludes apprenticeships, courses,etc). We will treat this variable as continuous, despite it’s descrete coding and limited range (0-17). This avoids a loss of degrees of freedom and possible overfitting, which would arise from encoding education as a categorical variable with 18 levels. This is also the case with the “gestate” variable - if we are going to treat the data as a a continuous variable, then ideally it would be encoded in terms of days (especially since this is a highly relevant factor near the mother’s data of birth).

Again, the profile of “smokers” varies considerably - the health impact of chain-smoking during a pregancy is likely to differ drastically to the impact of smoking one cigarette a week / day (which is not to say that either of these behaviours would likely be without deterimental effects, of course). Ideally there would be an additional variable for smoking indicating “low, moderate, heavy” or even an additional integer variable indicating the number of cigarettes usually smoked per day.

Perhaps the only variable measured, collected and structured in a way I agree with is the birth weight (response) variable itself. Measuring babies in grams to four significant figures allows for sufficient accuracy without making the data difficult to read.

What is also unclear, at the observation level, is whether the mother and child were alive after/during the birth. Mortality is often a key concern in pregnancy studies. Sometimes, stillborn births are excluded (see Southern Health Alliance reference) for data quality issues. However, we can not be sure whether this is the case. Given the minimum birth weight is ~300 grams, it is entirely possible stillborns are included in the data.

Finally, the most obvious predictor of birthweight - the mother’s weight, is not collected or factored into the dataset. Again, this is a major failing of the data as this intuitively would be responsible for a great deal of the variation in birthweights and possibly collinear with other indicators (ethnicity, smoking status) including other relevant indicators not included in the analysis (the mother’s age).

Pairwise plots

The next step is to look at correlations and distributions. Below are pairwise plots for the integer data. The correlations are Pearson’s correlations;

\[ r = \frac{n(\sum{xy}) - (\sum{x})(\sum{y})}{\sqrt{[(n\sum{x^{2}}-(\sum{x})^{2}][n\sum{y^{2}}-(\sum{y})^{2}]}} \]

# Function to return points and geom_smooth
# allow for the method to be changed
my_fn <- function(data, mapping, method="loess",...){

      geom_point() + 
      geom_smooth(method=method,se=F, ...)
      p
    }

There is quite a lot of information to digest here. Birthweight looks relatively normal with a long lefthand tail. Gestation period looks somewhat normal with a large spike around 40 weeks. Years of education recieved looks very peaky, a bimodal right hand tail. We will investigate these distributions in greater detail shortly.

Gestation period has a strong positive linear relationship with birthweight. Educational has almost no relationship with birthweight and education has almost no relationship with gestation period. These assessments from the scatterplots are supported by the correlation.

The majority of mothers are non smokers. There appear to be more black mothers who are smokers than non-black mothers who are smokers. However, while we are at it, we may as well run a chi-sq test for statistical significance. We are testing whether the factors are independant i.e. whether they (the categorical variables in question) have any statistically significant relationship. This is done by comparing the expected counts if there was no relationship with the observed counnts. This is just about the easiest statistical test to understand taking the form;

\[ \chi ^{2*} = \sum(O_i - E_i)^2 / E_i \]

summary(blackSmoke_crosstab.df)
## Call: xtabs(formula = ~black + smoke, data = births.df)
## Number of cases in table: 1115 
## Number of factors: 2 
## Test for independence of all factors:
##  Chisq = 3.0674, df = 1, p-value = 0.07988

It would appear that there is not a statistically significant difference (p > 0.05) in the number of mothers who smoke by ethnicity, although the level of statistical significance is marginal. Hence we keep the null hypothesis that the categories are indepedant. The p-value (0.08) approaches significance however, so it is perhaps something worth investigating in further detail.

Model selection

What do we wish to achieve with this data?

We wish to:

  • Maximise prediction accuracy
  • Explain as much of the variation in the data as possible
  • Avoid overfitting
  • Link our observational techniques to possible causal mechanisms

Simple models usually generalise to other datasets much more often than complicated models. Hence a key focus will be keeping the model simple.

Initialisation models

We start with several models that include most or all of the possible variables and interactions. For simplicity sake, we will avoid the issue of polynomial or square root terms in our model. We will leave aside any interpretation of the model until we have selected what we consider to be the “best” model, given the data, our knowledge and expertise and our time. small aside when entering boolean variables into the model, they are coerced into a factor with two levels: TRUE and FALSE. The model function then sorts these lexicographically (so that F is before T) - hat tip to SO user mnel

The supermodel below includes main effects, levels and all possible interactions, including even four-way interactions between the predictor variables. However, this may not lead to the best models selected when using the stepwise regression algorithm (“cold start problem”).

The “small” supermodel includes all main effects, levels and two way interactions, which are easier to explain and occur more oftenly in practice. We will develop both of these models further in the stepwise and subset regressions.

I have opted to just print the predictors, to emphasise that these models should not be considered viable final models. This leads to two intital models; one with 16 predictors and one with 11.

Stepwise regressions

Below is the results of running the automated stepwise regression routines. By default, R runs both the forwards and backwise routines, then compares the two models and selects the best one. By default, it does this on the basis of the Akakike information criterion. We can adjust the step function(set k = log(n)) to use BIC to find the best model - however as BIC is simply a varient on AIC that penalises larger models more heavily, this isn’t an especially productive exercise.

Subsets regression

We will use the ‘leaps’ package to compare all possible subsets for each number of predictors, rather than iteratively adding or dropping variables. This is possible because most criteria rely on the number of parameters - hence if this is held constant, we can use one measure to compare many subsets. This package can also perform forward and backwards stepwise regression, but here we are using it to perform an exhaustive search of all possible subsets of predictors (an ‘exhaustive’ search). We are starting from the large “supermodel” we defined before the stepwise regression stage.

Apologies for the small text size (just fitting the text on the plot required editing the package functions!).

#REF: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/21708764/cannot-change-text-size-in-regsubsets-plot
plot.regsubsets2 <- 
function (x, labels = obj$xnames, main = NULL, scale = c("bic", 
    "Cp", "adjr2", "r2"), col = gray(seq(0, 0.9, length = 10)), 
    ...) 
{
    obj <- x
    lsum <- summary(obj)
    par(mar = c(7, 5, 6, 3) + 0.1)
    nmodels <- length(lsum$rsq)
    np <- obj$np
    propscale <- FALSE
    sscale <- pmatch(scale[1], c("bic", "Cp", "adjr2", "r2"), 
        nomatch = 0)
    if (sscale == 0) 
        stop(paste("Unrecognised scale=", scale))
    if (propscale) 
        stop(paste("Proportional scaling only for probabilities"))
    yscale <- switch(sscale, lsum$bic, lsum$cp, lsum$adjr2, lsum$rsq)
    up <- switch(sscale, -1, -1, 1, 1)
    index <- order(yscale * up)
    colorscale <- switch(sscale, yscale, yscale, -log(pmax(yscale, 
        1e-04)), -log(pmax(yscale, 1e-04)))
    image(z = t(ifelse(lsum$which[index, ], colorscale[index], 
        NA + max(colorscale) * 1.5)), xaxt = "n", yaxt = "n", 
        x = (1:np), y = 1:nmodels, xlab = "", ylab = scale[1], 
        col = col)
    laspar <- par("las")
    on.exit(par(las = laspar))
    par(las = 2)
    axis(1, at = 1:np, labels = labels, ...) # I modified this line
    axis(2, at = 1:nmodels, labels = signif(yscale[index], 2))
    if (!is.null(main)) 
        title(main = main)
    box()
    invisible(NULL)
}

Please select the tabs below to see the interpretations for each criterion.

R-sq

r2Plot <- plot.regsubsets2(subsetsModel,scale = "r2", 
     main = "Optimal models and the R-sq",
     #labels = c("(Intercept)","Black","Smoke","Gestate","Educ",""),
     cex.axis = 0.5)

The first plot shows the ideal model (as measured by highest \(R^2\)) for each number of predictor variables, ordered by the model criterion we have plotted. We immediately see that large improvements in \(R^2\) are not obtained from higher numbers of predictor variables. I have plotted \(R^2\) as opposed to \(adjusted \, R^2\) as this is a nice illustration that \(R^2\) always increases with \(p\). It also nicely demonstrates that gestate (and the intercept) account for most of variance in birthweight. The simple model with only gestate in it has \(R^2\) = 0.49 - we can explain most of the variation that is able to be explained using our sets of main effects and interactions (as shown by the maximum \(R^2\) of 0.54) with just this simple model.

BIC

bicPlot <- plot.regsubsets2(subsetsModel,
     scale = "bic", 
     main = "Optimal models and BIC",
     cex.axis = 0.5)

For the formula for the Bayesian Information Criterion is;

\[ BIC = ln(n)k - 2 \, ln \, (\hat{L}) \]

Where \(k\) is the number of parameters, \(n\) is the number of observations and \(\hat{L}\) is the maximised log-likelihood.

This is refered to as a penalised-likilihood test. BIC, given many n (observations), is unlikely to choose a too large model, but may be more likely than AIC to choose a smaller model.

The second plot shows that the model that optimises BIC (lowest value) is the model with six terms (top of the chart). However, a reasonable compromise taking into account other criterion (and the practical difficulties in understanding and interpreting a three way interaction term) may be found by looking at the model with a BIC of -780 (6th row from bottom).

Mallow’s Cp

cpPlot <- plot.regsubsets2(subsetsModel,
     scale = "Cp", 
     main = "Optimal models and Mallow's CP",
     cex.axis = 0.5)

The broad ideas here are that we look for;

  • p != Cp (don’t use Cp to evaluate full model)
  • Cp near or below p (no bias)
  • Avoid large values of Cp (suggests important predictors are missing)
  • Then choose the simplest or most appropriate model

We find here very high Cp values for our simplistic models, suggesting they may be biased (underspecified), by not including enough variables or interactions. The model with a Cp value of 9.2 might be a good compromise between complexity and bias. Beyond that, at smaller Cp values, we are left with a variety of models which generally exclude educ but include different combinations of other interactions. We will address these when we review the criterion matrix later.

Adj. R-sq

\(R^2\) is calculated as follows;

\[R^{2}_a = 1 -\frac{RSS / (n-p)}{TSS / (n - 1)} \]

Hence we have a figure that is identical to \(R^2\) but is penalised by degrees of freedom. This accounts for the complexity of the model (number of parameters). This reflects a symptom of the data collection and study design discussed earlier: significant predictors that could explain variance in the data (alcohol consumptions, mothers weight etc) are not included in the dataset. It also informs us, given the data we have, models beyond more than four parameters (especially very complex models, as seen near the top of the chart) are probably not worth the loss of degrees of freedom and risk of overfitting.

adjr2Plot <- plot.regsubsets2(subsetsModel,
     scale = "adjr2", 
     main = "Optimal models and Adj. R-sq",
     cex.axis = 0.5)

We find that \(R^2\) is virtually identical for models with four or parameters - hence varying combinations of extra and increasing complex interactions are unlikely to explain a greater proportion of variation in the data.

We have reviewed the criterion plots for the subset regression.

Now that we know the optimal model for each \(p\), we must choose \(p\). This will essentially be a manual consideration of the tradeoff in complexity and fit of the model. This involves a comparison of the relevant criterion;

Unfortunately, this model includes a three way interaction term without including two way interaction terms. This is generally considered a fairly illogical selection - especially context. Why would ethnicity interact with the level of education only dependant on whether the mother is a smoker or not? If a model cannot pass a sanity test like this, and is not a clear standout then it should probably be abandoned in favour of an alternate approach.

At this point we could go back to our subsets algorithm and allow the two (or three) best models for each number of predictors to be included in the object from which we will extract coefficients and model terms. However, this is started to go down the road of data mining and is a redundant exercise for models with low numbers of parameters (which we intuitively think are likely).

We find that R-sq and adjusted R for the simple model are almost the same as the complex model selected by the stepwise regression! Is the more complex step-wise model superior to the simple model? Since the simple model is nested with the complex model, we can run an ANOVA (analysis of variance) to determine if there is a statistically significant difference how much of the variation in the response the model explains. This takes the form;

\[ F = \frac{(RSS_B - RSS_A) / (p - q)}{RSS_A /(n-p-1)} \]

Where p is the number of parameters in the small model and q is the number of parameters in the large model. Hence, we are testing whether the reduction in residual sums of squares (error) is significant, given the loss of degrees of freedom. The F values will take the form;

\[ F_{p-q,n-p-1} \]

anova(chosen_Model,stepWise_model)

However, rerunning this process, we find we are unable to delete any more terms from the model, as this would result in a statistically significant difference in the explanatory power of the model. Hence we will use this model for our final interpretation and look at the diagnostic plots to check we have not violated any assumptions.

Assumptions and transformations

Residual plots

autoplot(stepWise_dropOne.lm,
         alpha = 0.3,
         smooth.colour = 'red',
         ad.colour = 'darkred',
         label.size = 3,
         ad.size = 0.4,

In a nutshell: all is well.

  • The Normal Q-Q plot: the residuals fit the ECDF very well. There is some deviation at high residual values, likely due to the model not fitting high birthweights particulary well. Hence the assumption of the normality of the residuals is not violated.

  • The Residuals vs Fitted plot: the residuals are spread out in a fairly random pattern, there doesn’t appear to be any trend left in the residuals that we could model.

  • The Scale-Location plot: the residuals have a good degree of scatter across the range of the data. Again, due to the sparsity of low birthweight babies, residuals at low fitted values appear to have less variance. Hence the assumption of constant variance in the residuals is not violated.

  • The Residuals vs Leverage plot: the residuals generally have very low leverage, although they are quite large. No residuals are within the 0.5 cooks boundary (which is so far away it is not plotted), hence we can be confident that our regression has not been affected.

In summary, we do not need to worry about excluding influential points or transforming the predictors or response variables.

We could also produce a histogram of the residuals;

Quantitiative tests and indicators

To confirm that influential points are not an issue, I calculate the maximum cooks distance;

print("Max cooks distance")
## [1] "Max cooks distance"
max(cooks.distance(stepWise_dropOne.lm))
## [1] 0.02304157

To obtain more quantitative assurance of normality, we will run a shapiro test to check for normality of the residuals;

shapiro.test(stepWise_dropOne.lm$residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  stepWise_dropOne.lm$residuals
## W = 0.99843, p-value = 0.4094

As the p-value is greater than 0.05 we do not reject the null hypothesis that the residuals are drawn from a normal distribution.

To obtain more quantitative assurance of homoscedasticity , we will run a Breush Pagan test to check for homogeneity of variance in the residuals;

lmtest::bptest(stepWise_dropOne.lm) 
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  stepWise_dropOne.lm
## BP = 10.998, df = 6, p-value = 0.08845
ncvTest(stepWise_dropOne.lm) 
## Non-constant Variance Score Test 
## Variance formula: ~ fitted.values 
## Chisquare = 1.438162    Df = 1     p = 0.2304369

Uh oh! The Breusch-Pagan test was marginal (p = 0.09) and the NCV test was clearly significant (p = 0.02) - should we reject the null hypothesis of homoscedasticity? Fortunately, it turns out the ncvTest is implemented without studentising the test statistic. Hence it is much less robust to non-Gaussian kurtosis. Nonetheless, we can hardly be assured that the assumption has not been violated.

Unfortunately, due to time and technical constraints. We could try transforming the predictors, transforming the response or using Weight-Least-Squares (or a different estimator). We could try using the sandwhich estimator after fitting the lm model to calculate adjusted p-values. We could remove the spare portion of the data (premature, underweight births) but this would significantly reduce the utlity of the model. Hence we will have to acknowledge that some bias may have crept into the model here.

Link to discussion regarding BP Tests

To be thorough, we will create a boxcox plot and inspect the points labelled on the diagnostic plots. This is a valid procedure, as all of our response observations are greater than zero.

Box cox transformation

boxCox(stepWise_dropOne.lm,main = "BoxCox plot")

The formula for the boxcox transformation is; \[\begin{equation*} f(y) = \begin{cases} \frac{y^{\lambda}-1}{\lambda} \, \text{for } \lambda \neq 0 \\ log_e (y) \, \text{for } \lambda = 0 \end{cases} \end{equation*}\]

The suggested value of \(\lambda\) is 1, as indicated by the confidence bounds on the plot. We wish to maximise the log-likelihood (this is how MLE works). Plugging this into the equation yields the transformation \(\frac{y^{1}-1}{1}\) i.e. 1. Hence, no transformation is neccesary.

I have specified outliers to be shown on the diagnostic plots. We will investigate these individually, refering to them by row number;

We can see that several of the observations represent particulary heavy babies (1045,94) that are poorly modelled (because they have mothers that are African American or Smoke). Suprisingly, only one of the outliers (1084) on the diagnostic plots is an underweight baby - indicating that we have modelled low birthweight babies reasonably well. One observation (748) reflects a baby born with the expected normal gestation period, but has a suprisingly low birthweight (resulting in a very negative residual). The other two observations are cases where the babies were born with a reasonably healthy weight despite being born very early (119) or being born to an African American smoker and having an above average weight (987). The last observation (3) is an outlier due to having a very low value of education while still having a healthy birthweight.

A key point is that none of the outliers marked by the diagnostic plots are so unusual that they could be due to error, or reflect subgroups worth modelling seperately. Given our set of predictors (especially gestation period), a key outcome is very low birthweights, hence it would be unwise to filter out very low birthweight babies.

In conclusion, our model might not be perfect (especially regarding the issue of heteroscedasticity), but it meets enough assumptions that I feel transformations are not neccesary process to embark on. I also feel reasonably confident we can use this model.

While interpreting the coefficients, bear in mind that the all of the actual effects are equally likely to lie anywhere within the confidence intervals (with the usual caveat that the true population parameters may also lie outside these intervals). Just because one coefficient may lie near the bottom of it’s interval does not mean the same applies to the other coefficients. Hence, given the width of confidence intervals we have quite a range of true population parameters that could reflect the “true” model (given our data and predictors). We will address this further down. This is a similar idea (although not quite the same as it applies to the shape of GAMs) as illustrated here;

Illustration of uncertainty in GAMs

We find that;

  • The intercept of the model was found to be statistically significant and highly negative. Taken at face value (ignoring context) mothers who do not smoke, are not African American, have zero years of education and have zero weeks of gestation will have babies that weight -2595g. What does this mean? We will address this in detail below.

  • Smoking has a significant negative effect on birthweights; mothers who smoke and are not African American will have babies 334g lighter than non-smoking non-African American mothers on average.

  • African American ethnicity has a signficant negative effect on birthweights; mothers who are African American and do not smoke will have babies -666g lighter on average.

  • Due to the interaction with ethnicity and smoking, mothers who smoke and are also African American will not have the full deleterious main effects of smoking and ethnicity on birthweight; they will have babies (-666g + -335g + 251g = ) -750g lighter on average.

  • Education, while in the model, was not found to have a statistically significant main effect for non-African Americans (at the \(\alpha\) = 0.05 level of confidence).

  • However, the interaction of African American ethnicity and education was found to be statistically significant and positive. Given that a mother is African American, we expect each additional year of education to add (-9.3g + 35.6g = ) 26.3g to the birthweight of the baby.

  • Gestation period has a significant positive effect on birthweights; for each additional week a baby stays in the womb, we expect the birthweight of that baby to increase by 157g.

Given that the only significant, positive and non-categorical influence on birthweights is gestation period, it suggests a mother will need to have a baby who experiences at least 16.5 weeks in the womb to have a positive birthweight. Of course, we know that from the point of conception a baby’s weight is positive - hence interpreting the intercept in a literal sense is not logical.

The best way we can interpret this intercept is as a “lower bound” for gestational period. We know that babies born weighing less than 1500g are extremely underweight. Hence, holding all other factors constant (assuming the base level of the contrasts and zero educational level) we would anticipate that the minimal gestation period require to avoid having an extremely underweight baby is \(\frac{(2595 + 1500)}{157} = 26 \, weeks)\). This aligns with what we observed from birthweights in the dataset.

The \(R^2\) value is 0.54. This suggests the model explains 54% of the variation of birthweight. The F statistic is 213, which leads to a p-value of \(\approx 0\) - hence the model is highly significant (against the null hypothesis that the variation in birthweights could be equally well explained by a mean model).

We can also produce confidence intervals for our model;

The intervals shown gives us a practical understanding of the significance of education (alone) in our model: it isn’t (the population parameter could plausibly be zero). We can see some of the confidence intervals are quite wide, which has implications for evaluating the importance of certain factors involved in birthweights. For example, we might expect birthweights of African American babies (given that the mothers do not smoke and have 0 years of education) by as much as nearly approx. 1kg (!) or as little as approx. -350g (an effect small enough to be potentially mitigated by the beneficial interaction of ethnicity and education).

The positive interaction term African American:Smoking shows that this situation results in a less severe scenario (shown by the lower vertical distance of blue triangles and circles than red triangles and circle).

Context specific questions

Most of the suggested questions asked in the assignment have already been answered in the modelling process. However, we will provide a quick recap here;

  • Is there a difference in the average weight of children born to black and non-black mothers?
t.test((births.df$grams[births.df$black == T]),
       (births.df$grams[births.df$black == F]))
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  (births.df$grams[births.df$black == T]) and (births.df$grams[births.df$black == F])
## t = -9.0355, df = 1036.1, p-value < 2.2e-16

## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -402.4795 -258.8556
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  3085.193  3415.861

The t-test p-value for the difference in means is \(\approx 0\), hence we can be confident there is a significant differece in the average weight. This also reflects a practical different, being over \(\frac{1}{3}\) of a kilo.

  • Does smoking during pregnancy affect a baby’s birth weight?
t.test((births.df$grams[births.df$smoke == T]),
       (births.df$grams[births.df$smoke == F]))
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  (births.df$grams[births.df$smoke == T]) and (births.df$grams[births.df$smoke == F])
## t = -7.209, df = 400.02, p-value = 2.834e-12
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -429.7411 -245.5800
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  2963.338  3300.999

As above, there is a practical and significant difference in birth weights.

  • Is it sensible to use this model to describe the rate at which a baby puts on weight over a pregnancy?

Probably not. As we have shown, the model can not backwards extrapolate below the range of the observed data accurately. It is unlikely the foetal weight varies in the linear way described by the model - this is an appropriate approximation, given the range of the observed data, but inappropriate for modelling the whole pregancy period. We could perhaps infer a rate of change in foetal weight from the relationship of gestation period and birthweights, but this would probably not accurately reflect the actual process of foetal development that occurs - the data concerns livebirths, not fetuses.

  • Are there any extremely premature babies (the typical gestational period for humans is 40 weeks) who influence the fit of this model, and should they have this influence?

As we established during the diagnostics stage of the modelling process, no data points are even close to a large cooks distance. Some of the points have relatively high leverage, but the model seems to fit them well. Furthermore, part of the intention of the model is modelling the birthweight of premature babies. It is directly observable that there is a wide spread of birthweights at the normal gestation period, likely due to the influence of unmeasured factors (e.g. maternal weight).

  • Are the effects of any variable different for different levels of another variable e.g. does the longer a mother experiences in education have the same relationship with birth weight for black and non-black mothers?

Our model includes two interactions; smoking and ethnicity, and education and ethnicity. These terms have been fully explained in previous sections.

Volmes and Rates combinations

To begin, we will need the coefficients of both models as vector. We also need to work out what a probability of 0.1 is once it has been transformed by the link function. The backtransformed probability is;

\[ log(\frac{p}{1-p}) \]

log(0.1/(1-0.1)) -> target_logit

The coefficients are;

coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec <- coef(logit_vaso.mod)
coef_logged_logit_vaso_mod.vec <- coef(logged_logit_vaso.mod)

We can shift the intercept to the other side of this equation. Hence we find we are solving for two unknowns. We can get around this by creating reasonable vectors (\(R_i,V_i\)) for a range of values for one of the unknowns;

\[ \]

sample_breath_volumes <- seq(from = 0, to = 4, by = 0.001) 
sample_breath_rates <- seq(from  = 0, to = 4, by = 0.001)

Then we solve for estimated combinations of volume and rate, for the logit model;

To find a rate for a given volume we use;

\[ \frac{log(\frac{p}{1-p}) - \beta_0 \, / \,\beta_1V_i}{\beta_2} = R_i \] To find a volume for a given rate we use;

\[ \frac{log(\frac{p}{1-p}) - \beta_0 \, / \,\beta_2R_i}{\beta_3} = V_i \]

This is implemented programmatically below;

#system we wish to solve
#coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec[1] + coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec[2]*sample_breath_rates + coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec[3]*Unknown.mat = target_logit

pointOne_volumes <- NULL; pointOne_rates <- NULL

i = 1
for (i in 1:length(sample_breath_rates)) {
pointOne_volumes[i] = ((target_logit - coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec[1])/(coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec[2]*sample_breath_volumes[i])/coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec[3])
}

pointOne_logModel_VOLUME.df <- data.frame(cbind(pointOne_volumes,sample_breath_rates))
colnames(pointOne_logModel_VOLUME.df) <- c("Volume","Rate")

i = 1
for (i in 1:length(sample_breath_volumes)) {
pointOne_rates[i] = ((target_logit - coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec[1])/(coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec[3]*sample_breath_rates[i])/coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec[2])
}
rm(i)

pointOne_logModel_RATE.df <- data.frame(cbind(pointOne_rates,sample_breath_volumes))
colnames(pointOne_logModel_RATE.df) <- c("Rate","Volume")

We can then use these dataframes for prediction. We then sift through these predictions to find the closest two combinations of points that lead to a 0.1 probability of vasoconstriction;

VOLUME_combo_predictions.vec <- predict(logit_vaso.mod,pointOne_logModel_VOLUME.df,type = 'response')
RATE_combo_predictions.vec <- predict(logit_vaso.mod,pointOne_logModel_RATE.df,type = 'response')

rate_combo_logit <- Closest(RATE_combo_predictions.vec,0.1);volume_combo_logit <- Closest(VOLUME_combo_predictions.vec,0.1)

logitVOULMEpoint <- (pointOne_logModel_VOLUME.df[as.numeric(names(volume_combo_logit)),])
logitRATEpoint <- (pointOne_logModel_RATE.df[as.numeric(names(rate_combo_logit)),])

We end up with two dataframes, suggesting a rate for each sample volume and a volume for each sample rate. We find two combination of values that predict a 0.1 probability of vasoconstriction. In practice this is probably a line across the response surface, but for now I am unsure (and have run out of time) on how to solve this.

Now we solve for estimated combinations of volume and rate, for the logged predictors logit model. This is a similar progress, but the equations actually simplify neatly.

To find a rate for a given volume we use;

\[ \frac{log(\frac{p}{p-0.1}) - log(\beta_0) \, / \,log(\beta_1V_i)}{log(\beta_2)} = log(R_i) \]

This simplifies into;

\[ \frac{\frac{p}{p-0.1} - \beta_0 \, / \,\beta_1V_i}{\beta_2} = R_i \]

To find a volume for a given rate we use;

\[ \frac{log(\frac{p}{1-p}) - log(\beta_0) \, / \,log(\beta_2R_i)}{log(\beta_3)} = log(V_i) \]

This simplifies into;

\[ \frac{\frac{p}{1-p} - \beta_0 \, / \,\beta_2R_i}{\beta_3} = V_i \]

Because of this simplification, the backtransformation of the probability is simpler;

target_logit_2 <- (0.1/(1-0.1))

We log the reasonable predictors, as this is the form of the logged logit model.

log_sample_breath_volumes <- log(seq(from = 0, to = 4, by = 0.001))
log_sample_breath_rates <- log(seq(from  = 0, to = 4, by = 0.001))

But otherwise the process follows as before (with some backtransforming inside the algorithm to account for what logging is going and what the R predict function will expect as input);

#system we wish to solve
#coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec[1] + coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec[2]*sample_breath_rates + coef_logit_vaso_mod.vec[3]*Unknown.mat = target_logit

pointOne_logged_volumes <- NULL; pointOne_logged_rates <- NULL

i = 1
for (i in 1:length(log_sample_breath_rates)) {
pointOne_logged_volumes[i] = ((target_logit - coef_logged_logit_vaso_mod.vec[1])/(coef_logged_logit_vaso_mod.vec[2]*log_sample_breath_volumes[i])/coef_logged_logit_vaso_mod.vec[3])
}

pointOne_logged_logModel_VOLUME.df <- data.frame(cbind(exp(pointOne_logged_volumes),exp(log_sample_breath_rates)))
colnames(pointOne_logged_logModel_VOLUME.df) <- c("Volume","Rate")

i = 1
for (i in 1:length(log_sample_breath_volumes)) {
pointOne_logged_rates[i] = ((target_logit - coef_logged_logit_vaso_mod.vec[1])/(coef_logged_logit_vaso_mod.vec[3]*log_sample_breath_rates[i])/coef_logged_logit_vaso_mod.vec[2])
}
rm(i)

pointOne_logged_logModel_RATE.df <- data.frame(cbind(exp(pointOne_logged_rates),exp(log_sample_breath_volumes)))
colnames(pointOne_logged_logModel_RATE.df) <- c("Rate","Volume")

Again, we can then use these dataframes for prediction. We then sift through these predictions to find the closest two combinations of points that lead to a 0.1 probability of vasoconstriction for the logged logit model;

VOLUME_combo_logged_predictions.vec <- predict(logged_logit_vaso.mod,pointOne_logged_logModel_VOLUME.df,type='response')
RATE_combo_logged_predictions.vec <- predict(logged_logit_vaso.mod,pointOne_logged_logModel_RATE.df,type = 'response')

rate_combo_logged_logit <- Closest(RATE_combo_logged_predictions.vec,0.1);volume_combo_logged_logit <- Closest(VOLUME_combo_logged_predictions.vec,0.1)

loggedlogitVOULMEpoint <- (pointOne_logged_logModel_VOLUME.df[as.numeric(names(volume_combo_logged_logit)),])
loggedlogitRATEpoint <- (pointOne_logged_logModel_RATE.df[as.numeric(names(rate_combo_logged_logit)),])

We now wrap these four points into a dataframe for the scatterplot;

modelPointsP1.df <- rbind(loggedlogitRATEpoint,loggedlogitVOULMEpoint,logitRATEpoint,logitVOULMEpoint)

Plot the points used for predictions

Finally, we can plot the points that generate a probability of 0.1, in addition to the points used in the predictions earlier, onto the original scatterplot.

ggplot(data = vaso.df) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(y = Rate, x = Volume,shape = Response,color = Response),size = 2) +
  geom_point(data = newvaso.df,mapping = aes(y = Rate,x = Volume),color = 'purple') +
  geom_point(data = modelPointsP1.df,mapping = aes(y = Rate,x = Volume),color = 'green') +
  labs(title = "Scatterplot of Rate and Volume",
       y = "Rate (l/s intake of breath)",
       x = "Volume (l per breath)",
       caption = "data sourced from Finney's 1947 vasoconstriction data",
       subtitle = "purple points indicate predictions | 0.1 vasoconstriction probability combinations shown in green") + 
  theme_tufte()
